by":0,"total_blocked_by":0,"blocking":0,"total_blocking":0},"body":"### Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe it\n\n`app.useWebSocketAdapter(adapter)` is the only API to swap the `IoAdapter`. Per `packages/core/nest-application.ts`, `init()` runs in this order:\n\n```ts\nasync init() {\n  this.applyOptions();\n  await this.httpAdapter?.init?.();\n  // ...\n  await this.registerModules();   // socketModule.register() bootstraps gateways\n  await this.registerRouter();    //   using whatever IoAdapter is on\n  await this.callInitHook();      //   ApplicationConfig RIGHT NOW\n  // ...\n}\n```\n\n`socketModule.register()` reads the adapter from `ApplicationConfig` during `registerModules()`. `callInitHook()` (which fires every module's `OnModuleInit`) runs **after**.\n\nNet effect: `app.useWebSocketAdapter(...)` called from any `OnModuleInit` hook silently no-ops. Gateways have already been wired with the default `IoAdapter`. No warning, no log line, no error — the app boots, gateways respond on the default `/socket.io/` path, and any feature carried by the custom adapter (Redis pub/sub fan-out via `@socket.io/redis-adapter`, a custom engine `path`, TLS-bound HTTP server, etc.) is silently inert.\n\nEvery other configurable dependency in NestJS is resolvable through DI via `forRootAsync` — TypeORM, JWT, Throttler, Mongoose, Bull, etc. — and the framework reads the resolved provider when it needs it. The `IoAdapter` is the lone exception. Because it must be set before `registerModules()` runs and `OnModuleInit` fires after, there is no NestJS-blessed way to install an adapter whose configuration depends on other providers (e.g. a `ConfigService` that supplies the Redis URI, a custom engine `path`, a Sentry hook, etc.).\n\nThe only place that works is `main.ts`, between `NestFactory.create()` and `app.listen()`:\n\n```ts\nconst app = await NestFactory.create(AppModule, ...);\napp.useWebSocketAdapter(new MyAdapter(app, /* config? hardcoded or resolved manually */));\nawait app.listen(port);\n```\n\nThis forces every consumer to either (a) hardcode adapter config in `main.ts`, breaking the encapsulation the module system is designed for, or (b) resolve providers manually via `app.get(...)` in `main.ts` and pass them into the adapter, which leaks infrastructure config out of the module that owns it.\n\nA library that exports a `WebsocketModule.forRootAsync({ useFactory: (config) => ... })` to wire a Redis adapter looks correct, type-checks, runs `OnModuleInit`, calls `app.useWebSocketAdapter(...)`, and produces a fully broken setup that nothing flags.\n\n### Describe the solution you'd like\n\nLong-term: make the adapter resolvable from the DI container — a well-known token (e.g. `WS_IO_ADAPTER`) that `registerWsModule()` resolves via `container.get(...)` at init time, with `useWebSocketAdapter(...)` continuing to work as the imperative override. That lets module authors write:\n\n```ts\n@Module({\n  providers: [\n    {\n      provide: WS_IO_ADAPTER,\n      useFactory: (c: ConfigService) => new MyAdapter(c.get('REDIS_URI')),\n      inject: [ConfigService],\n    },\n  ],\n})\nexport class WebsocketModule {}\n```\n\nand have it actually work, with the same compositional ergonomics as every other `forRootAsync` in the framework.\n\n**Minimum acceptable change**, even if the DI integration is rejected as out of scope: the silent no-op should not exist. `ApplicationConfig.setIoAdapter()` (or `useWebSocketAdapter` directly on `NestApplication`) should detect that `socketModule.register()` has already run and either:\n\n- `Logger.warn(...)` loudly that the adapter swap is ineffective and the gateways are already bound to the previous adapter, or\n- throw in strict mode (e.g. when `abortOnError !== false` or behind a new opt-in flag)\n\nThree or four lines of code. Zero compatibility impact for users doing the right thing. The next person hitting this gets a one-line answer in their logs instead of a multi-day debug session.\n\n### Teachability, documentation, adoption, migration strategy\n\nFor the DI-resolvable adapter, the migration is opt-in and additive — existing apps using `useWebSocketAdapter` in `main.ts` continue to work unchanged. Documentation under `docs/websockets/adapter` would gain a \"DI-resolvable adapter\" subsection alongside the current `bootstrap()` pattern, showing the `WS_IO_ADAPTER` provider form. For the warning/throw, no migration needed — only consumers who were silently broken get a new log line.\n\nFor anyone hitting this today, the pattern that works inside the framework's existing seams without monkey-patching: add an `onAppReady(fn)` listener to whatever service holds the resolved `INestApplication` (most apps already have one for `setApp(app)`), have it fire synchronously inside `setApp`, and move adapter installation out of `OnModuleInit` into the module's constructor (which runs during `NestFactory.create()` and registers the callback before `app.listen()` runs `init()`):\n\n```ts\n// IAppContext (one service in a shared lib)\npublic setApp(app: INestApplication): void {\n  this._app = app;\n  for (const fn of this.listeners) fn(app);   // sync, between create and listen\n}\n\n// WebsocketModule\npublic constructor(\n  @Inject(IWebsocketOptions) opts: IWebsocketOptions,\n  @Inject(IAppContext) appContext: IAppContext<INestApplication>,\n) {\n  appContext.onAppReady((app) => {\n    app.useWebSocketAdapter(new CustomIoAdapter(app, opts));\n  });\n}\n\n// main.ts — unchanged, every service has this already\nconst app = await NestFactory.create(AppModule, ...);\napp.get<IAppContext>(IAppContext).setApp(app);   // ← adapter installs synchronously here\nawait app.listen(port);\n```\n\nThis is uglier than `forRootAsync` would be, but it's the only way to compose adapter config from DI without touching framework internals.\n\n### What is the motivation / use case for changing the behavior?\n\nWe hit this in production: a `WebsocketModule.forRootAsync({ useFactory: (config) => ... })` that read a Redis URI and a custom Socket.IO engine `path` from `ConfigService`, installed the adapter via `useWebSocketAdapter` inside `OnModuleInit`. Looked correct, compiled, booted, every gateway responded — and the custom engine `path` never took effect because Socket.IO was still on `/socket.io/` from the default adapter. Ingress was routing the custom path, got 404 from the framework, returned errors to clients. The Redis adapter we thought was wired across replicas was sitting unused because the in-memory default was silently in place. It took several hours of debugging through `nest-application.ts` to find the timing mismatch.\n\nThe general use case is \"I want to install a custom `IoAdapter` whose configuration depends on other providers\" — Redis URIs from config, custom paths from infrastructure modules, observability hooks from a Sentry module. Today that requires either main.ts boilerplate (per-service, leaks infra config) or framework-prototype monkey-patching. Neither matches the compositional model that every other configurable thing in NestJS follows.\n\n### PR willingness\n\nHappy to PR the warning/throw on `ApplicationConfig.setIoAdapter()` post-init. The DI-resolvable-adapter feature is bigger and would benefit from a maintainer ack on direction before I start.\n\n### Environment\n\n- `@nestjs/core@11.x` (verified on 11.1.19)\n- `@nestjs/websockets`, `@nestjs/platform-socket.io`\n- `@nestjs/platform-fastify` (also reproduces on Express)","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/nestjs/nest/issues/16992/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"timeline_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/nestjs/nest/issues/16992/timeline","performed_via_github_app":null,"state_reason":"completed","pinned_comment":null,"score":1.0}],"search_type":"lexical"}